## Context

Audit 0070 flagged bias **B3** (English-language dominance) as ⚠
mitigated: BGE-M3 places multiple languages in a shared space, but the
shared space is trained on predominantly English + Chinese web text.
Representation quality is uneven, which can bias the semantic (S2) and
lexical (L1) channels toward language-similarity rather than
structural similarity. §6.4 acknowledges the model choice but does not
report a language-stratified test.

The pipeline already produces per-record language labels
(`scripts/enrich_language.py`), so the data is available.

## Actions

1. Build an English-only subset of `refined_works` using the `language`
   field (keep records where language = 'en' with confidence above
   threshold). Count the share kept per year.
2. Re-run S2 cosine and L1 JS divergence on the English-only subset.
   Use the same windows and seed as the main analysis.
3. Compare transition zones: do the 2007 and 2013 breakpoints survive
   the English-only restriction? Produce an overlay plot.
4. If zones shift by more than ±1 year, qualify the multilingual claim
   in §6.4 with one sentence.

## Test

`tests/test_language_stratified.py::test_english_subset_has_breakpoints`
— asserts that S2 on the English subset produces a breakpoints CSV with
the same schema as the full run. Red until the stratified runner exists.

## Exit criteria

- A stratified run config that reproducibly regenerates the English-only
  divergence outputs.
- An overlay figure in the supplementary material.
- A paragraph in §4.8 or §6.4 summarizing the result.
